# Database & Migration Guidelines

## Database Schema

### Core Models
- **Vendor**: Pet protectors (individuals/NGOs)
- **VendorAdmin**: Users associated with vendors
- **Report**: Content moderation reports
- **Product**: Pet listings (extended Medusa model)
- **User**: Medusa's built-in user model

### Model Relationships
```typescript
// Vendor has many VendorAdmins
Vendor -> VendorAdmin (one-to-many)

// VendorAdmin belongs to User
VendorAdmin -> User (many-to-one)

// Report targets various entities
Report -> Product (polymorphic)
Report -> Vendor (polymorphic)
```

## Migration Patterns

### Creating Migrations
```bash
# Generate migration
npx medusa db:generate migration-name

# Apply migrations
npx medusa db:migrate

# Rollback (if needed)
npx medusa db:revert
```

### Migration Best Practices
- **Version control** all migration files
- **Test migrations** on development database first
- **Backup database** before production migrations
- **Atomic operations** - migrations should be reversible
- **Data migrations** separate from schema migrations

## Model Definition

### MikroORM Patterns
```typescript
@Entity()
export class Vendor {
  @PrimaryKey()
  id!: string

  @Property()
  name!: string

  @Property()
  email!: string

  @Property({ nullable: true })
  phone?: string

  @Property({ nullable: true })
  address?: string

  @Property({ default: false })
  is_active!: boolean

  @OneToMany(() => VendorAdmin, admin => admin.vendor)
  admins = new Collection<VendorAdmin>(this)

  @OneToMany(() => Report, report => report.vendor)
  reports = new Collection<Report>(this)
}
```

